    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned something about needing an escrow account for this house i'm looking at in toronto. i've never bought a place before so i'm kinda lost. can u explain what escrow actually is and why it's even used in the closing process?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "An escrow account is essentially a neutral third-party holding account where funds and documents are temporarily stored until the closing of a real estate transaction. In Toronto, this is crucial because it ensures that the buyer's money is safe from the seller and the seller's funds are secured for the buyer until all conditions are met. It protects both parties by preventing any premature transfers or disputes over the condition of the property before the final paperwork is signed. Think of it like a secure vault that only the lawyer or title company can access, ensuring the deal closes fairly and legally. You can't really buy a house in Toronto without this step, as it's a standard requirement for protecting your financial interests.\n\nIt's a bit like a trusted bank guard who holds the keys to the treasure chest until everyone agrees it's time to open it. Without this middleman, there's a risk that someone might try to take the money or the deed before everything is in order. For a first-time buyer, understanding escrow helps you feel more confident that the process is structured to keep you safe from scams or errors. Just remember, once the escrow is closed, those funds and documents are officially transferred, and the transaction is complete. If you have questions about the specific",
      "source": "target",
