    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks that makes sense. so is the person holding the money like just a random person or is it always a law firm? and how do they make sure the money doesn't just... get lost or taken by someone else while it's sitting there?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The person holding the money isn't just a random individual; in Toronto, it is almost always a licensed title company or a specific law firm that acts as the neutral escrow agent. They are highly regulated professionals who must follow strict banking and legal protocols to ensure the funds remain safe and accessible only when the closing conditions are met. If you're worried about the money disappearing, that's a valid concern, but these institutions are required to segregate client funds from their own operating accounts, which prevents commingling and theft. They also perform due diligence checks, like verifying the property's title and ensuring the seller has paid off existing mortgages, before releasing any funds to the buyer or lender.\n\nThink of it as a very strict, rule-following bank vault that only opens when a specific, pre-agreed checklist of tasks is completed. If you ever feel like the process is dragging on or that funds are missing, you can contact the escrow agent directly to get an update on the status of your transaction. It's a bit like hiring a professional security guard for your house who won't let you move in until the front door is actually locked and the perimeter is secure. Just remember, if you're ever in a bind, you always have",
